    <title>Combined summary - Useful bitcoin patches...</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T17:00:46.709166+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-July/000085.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In 2011, there were several discussions on IRC, email, and the Bitcoin-development mailing list about improving the performance of Bitcoin. The main focus was on adding features such as multithreading the RPC, implementing Keep-Alive, and fixing bugs, with the aim of increasing speed and efficiency while minimizing unnecessary network usage.Jeff Garzik shared a link to a new version of Bitcoin called "bitcoin-3diff.txt" that had HTTP/1.1 keep-alive support among other features useful to big pools. Luke-Jr posted a new version of "bitcoin-4diff.txt", but hadn't compared it yet. He suggested several branches that he thinks should be merged, such as hub_mode, threaded_rpc, signal_blk_notify, and more. However, Matt Corallo disagreed with merging some of those branches because they could harm the network.Additionally, Christian Decker suggested that multithreading the RPC and adding Keep-Alive to the code of Bitcoin would be beneficial, but these changes require aggressive testing to ensure they don't expose race conditions in the code. The proposal for a 'hub mode' to optimize connection logic for all nodes was not accepted by everyone. Instead, miners should manually addnode each other to improve block propagation speed.There was also a discussion about lowering fees for Bitcoin transactions. Luke-Jr argued that developers should not interfere with users who want to pay lower fees and go to pools willing to do business. On the other hand, Matt Corallo believes that the issue is not about forcing users to pay anything but rather finding a solution to prevent random spamming in the chain.Overall, the conversations highlight ongoing debates over how best to handle transaction fees and network optimization in the Bitcoin network. The need for careful consideration and testing when implementing changes to the Bitcoin code was emphasized.</summary>
